            <section class="article-chapter">
                <div class="chapter-number">06</div>
                <h2 class="chapter-title">Why Fractional Shares Change Everything</h2>
                <p class="article-text">Nvidia trades at $900. Tesla at $250. Apple at $180.</p>
                <p class="article-text">Without fractional shares, you need $900 minimum to buy ONE Nvidia share. That's
                    ‚Çπ75,000+.</p>
                <p class="article-text"><strong>With fractional shares:</strong> You can buy 0.1 Nvidia for $90. Or 0.01
                    Nvidia for $9.</p>
                <div class="example-box">
                    <div class="example-header"> <span class="example-icon"></span> <span>Real Example: ‚Çπ10,000
                            Portfolio</span> </div>
                    <p class="article-text"><strong>WITHOUT Fractional Shares (Groww, ICICI):</strong></p>
                    <ul class="article-list">
                        <li>Can't buy Nvidia ($900 = too expensive)</li>
                        <li>Buy 2 Tesla shares ($250 √ó 2 = $500)</li>
                        <li>Buy 1 Microsoft ($400)</li>
                        <li>Leftover: $100 sitting idle</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p class="article-text"><strong>WITH Fractional Shares (Vested, Ind Money):</strong></p>
                    <ul class="article-list">
                        <li>0.33 shares Nvidia = $300</li>
                        <li>1.2 shares Tesla = $300</li>
                        <li>0.75 shares Microsoft = $300</li>
                        <li>Leftover: <strong>$0</strong> (100% invested!)</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p class="article-text" style="margin-top: 1rem; color: #4ade80;"><strong>Fractional shares = better
                            diversification + zero idle cash.</strong></p>
                </div>
                <blockquote class="article-quote">
                    <p>"I used to think fractional shares were gimmicky. Then I realized I could build a $500 portfolio
                        with 7 different tech stocks instead of buying 1-2 full shares. Game changer."</p>
                    <footer>‚Äî Priya, Mumbai</footer>
                </blockquote>
            </section> <!-- Tax Implications -->
            <section class="article-chapter">
                <div class="chapter-number">07</div>
                <h2 class="chapter-title">Tax Nightmare: What They Don't Tell You</h2>
                <div class="warning-box">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-exclamation-triangle"></i> Double Taxation Reality</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>US TDS (Tax Deducted at Source):</strong> 15% on dividends, 25% on capital gains
                            (can be reduced with DTAA treaty)</li>
                        <li><strong>Indian Capital Gains Tax:</strong> 20% with indexation (LTCG after 24 months) OR as
                            per your income tax slab (STCG)</li>
                        <li><strong>Foreign Tax Credit:</strong> You can claim credit for US tax paid when filing Indian
                            ITR (but paperwork is hell)</li>
                        <li><strong>LRS Reporting:</strong> Every transaction must be reported to RBI if total exceeds
                            $250k/year</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <p class="article-text"><strong>Good News:</strong> Modern brokers auto-handle most of this. Vested and
                    Ind Money file W-8BEN forms automatically, reducing US withholding from 30% to 15%.</p>
                <p class="article-text"><strong>Bad News:</strong> Indian ITR filing is still your responsibility.
                    Budget ‚Çπ3,000-5,000 for a CA if you have US stocks.</p>
                <div class="example-box">
                    <div class="example-header"> <span class="example-icon">üìä</span> <span>Real Tax Calculation:
                            $10,000 Profit</span> </div>
                    <p class="article-text"><strong>Scenario:</strong> You bought Tesla at $200, sold at $320. Profit =
                        $120 per share. 100 shares = $12,000 profit.</p>
                    <div class="pnl-display">
                        <div class="pnl-row"> <span class="pnl-label">Gross Profit:</span> <span
                                class="pnl-value">$12,000</span> </div>
                        <div class="pnl-row"> <span class="pnl-label">US Withholding (15%):</span> <span
                                class="pnl-value">-$1,800</span> </div>
                        <div class="pnl-row"> <span class="pnl-label">Indian LTCG Tax (20% on remaining):</span> <span
                                class="pnl-value">-$2,040</span> </div>
                        <div class="pnl-row"> <span class="pnl-label"><strong>Net After-Tax Profit:</strong></span>
                            <span class="pnl-value pnl-profit"><strong>$8,160</strong></span> </div>
                        <div class="pnl-row"> <span class="pnl-label"><strong>Effective Tax Rate:</strong></span> <span
                                class="pnl-value pnl-loss"><strong>~32%</strong></span> </div>
                    </div>
                    <p class="article-text" style="margin-top: 1rem;">üëâ <strong>32% tax</strong> is still worth it if
                        stock gave you 60%+ returns. But know what you're getting into.</p>
                </div>
            </section> <!-- Decision Framework -->
